Getting the Data Together

This document details the collection and maniplation of nine sets of data pulled from Twitter into one large dataset.

For the collection, I used the following script to collect data on nine separate dates:

'
# load twitter library - the rtweet library is recommended now over twitteR
library(rtweet)

# Enter your Twitter credentials
appname <- "hard_rock"  # name I assigned my app in Twitter
key <- "XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX"
secret <- "XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX"

# create token named "twitter_token"
twitter_token <- create_token(
  app = appname,
  consumer_key = key,
  consumer_secret = secret)

saveRDS(twitter_token, "~/.rtweet-oauth.rds")

# Scrape tweets
rstats_tweets <- search_tweets2(q = "Hard Rock Hotel OR Hard Rock Casino OR HardRockHCAC", n = 15000, parse = TRUE, type="mixed")

# Save tweets to a RData file
save(rstats_tweets, file="rtweetsyyyymmdd.RData")

'

A few notes: I used “XXXX” for my key and secret variables, since those are unique to each user and I do not want anyone to be able to get them. To get your own credentials, you can sign up for them at Twitter, you just need an account. Also, this may be self-explanitory, in the name at the end of the code that I saved my data as, yyyymmdd is the date.

I ran this code on the dates: June 3, June 9, June 14, June 19, June 25, July 1, July 7, July 11, and July 16, all in the year 2018. I will say that I got this code from one of my Professors, Dr. Clifton Baldwin, and didn’t change too much since it was minimalist already. Since this is not the main code, I felt that changing it to be more of my own wasn’t necessary. What comes after this is all mine, however.

Let’s get all of these datasets loaded in, and take a look at them. I want to examine their structure, and also merge them into one large dataset. I want to then transfer this dataset to Python to analyze the data. I chose Python simply because I am more familiar with it, though if the transfer becomes too much I will just use R instead.

load(file="rtweets20180603.RData")
rstats_tweets # Display the tweets!

Obviously, most of this data is not going to be useful to my study, so I will trim the fat, so to speak.

library(rtweet) # I load this in again because the first chunk should not be ran since it will just return an error.
users1 <- users_data(rstats_tweets) # Gets data relevant to the users from the rstats_tweets dataframe
users1

Users_data is a function in rtweet that extracts all of the relevant user information out of each of the tweets sent. I also want to keep the actual tweets themselves that were collected.

tweets1 <- rstats_tweets[,c("screen_name","text","created_at")] # I keep these in one dataframe for later.
tweets1

Awesome. That is all that I will need for this analysis. Time to get the rest of them.

load(file="rtweets20180609.RData")
users2 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)
tweets2 <- rstats_tweets[,c("screen_name","text","created_at")]
load(file="rtweets20180614.RData")
users3 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)
tweets3 <- rstats_tweets[,c("screen_name","text","created_at")]
load(file="rtweets20180619.RData")
users4 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)
tweets4 <- rstats_tweets[,c("screen_name","text","created_at")]
load(file="rtweets20180625.RData")
users5 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)
tweets5 <- rstats_tweets[,c("screen_name","text","created_at")]
load(file="rtweets20180701.RData")
users6 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)
tweets6 <- rstats_tweets[,c("screen_name","text","created_at")]
load(file="rtweets20180707.RData")
users7 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)

load(file="rtweets20180711.RData")
users8 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)

load(file="rtweets20180716.RData")
users9 <- users_data(rstats_tweets)
tweets9 <- rstats_tweets[,c("screen_name","text","created_at")]
users <- rbind(users1,users2,users3,users4,users5,users6,users7,users8,users9) # Merge all of the users data frames into one
tweets <- rbind(tweets1,tweets2,tweets3,tweets4,tweets5,tweets6,tweets7,tweets8,tweets9) # Merge all of the tweets data frames into one
rm(tweets1,tweets2,tweets3,tweets4,tweets5,tweets6,tweets7,tweets8,tweets9,users1,users2,users3,users4,users5,users6,users7,users8,users9,rstats_tweets) # Clean up a bit

During the collection, I attempted to make it so that the tweets were collected in overlapping sections. This results in a complete span of tweets, but with duplicates. And so, I will remove the duplicates here.

users <- unique(users)
tweets <- unique(tweets)

Out of 15672 tweets collected, only 9312 were not duplicated, and I collected data on 12203 users.

Saving these files using feather in order to transfer them to Python.

library(feather)
write_feather(tweets, "tweets")
write_feather(users, "users")

And with that, I should be good to go in Python!
